00:08:52.920 --> 00:09:03.740
That was in 1915 when he showed that light was actually affected by gravity so that light would bend around heavy objects because of this bend in the space time.

00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:11.520
And then a year later, Carl Schwarzschild found the first kind of real solution to Einstein's theory, to Einstein's equations,

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:19.120
which ended up in what we call the singularity, which showed that there is this object that is kind of a hole in the space time.

00:09:19.120 --> 00:09:23.300
And this object has a horizon, which we call the event horizon.

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:28.700
And the size of the horizon, the radius is called now the Schwarzschild radius after Carl Schwarzschild.

00:09:28.700 --> 00:09:36.020
And it showed that anything that goes beyond this horizon can never come back because the escape speed at the horizon is the speed of light.

00:09:36.020 --> 00:09:40.060
So anything that goes beyond would need an escape speed higher than the speed of light.

00:09:40.060 --> 00:09:42.080
So, and light is the fastest thing that goes.

00:09:42.080 --> 00:09:42.600
So nothing.

00:09:42.600 --> 00:09:48.080
Circle around and just kind of just somehow, probably still move, but still be trapped within that space.

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:48.540
Exactly.

00:09:48.540 --> 00:09:52.120
So you can never, once you cross that point, you can never come back.

00:09:52.420 --> 00:09:58.980
And at that time, so people thought a lot about the theory of Einstein and this mathematical object that we call the singularity.

00:09:58.980 --> 00:10:04.120
At the time they thought, okay, black holes are a mathematical object, but there's no way they could be real, right?

00:10:04.120 --> 00:10:09.840
So people thought, okay, mathematically, that's so interesting, but these things can't exist in the universe.

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:16.400
And then in the 1930s, Chandrasekhar, famous Indian astronomer, he thought about the mass of stars.

00:10:16.400 --> 00:10:19.920
So they're, you know, stars when they die, they become white dwarfs.

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:23.180
And so they die in these kind of stellar dead stars.

00:10:23.180 --> 00:10:25.500
But then he thought, what about more massive stars?

00:10:25.500 --> 00:10:26.660
Stars are much heavier.

00:10:26.660 --> 00:10:31.380
It turns out that he calculated it and white dwarfs have a maximum mass.

00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:39.320
So there are certain classes of heavier stars that could never end up as white dwarfs because they would collapse to something more massive than a white dwarf.

00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:40.640
So it could not be a white dwarf.

00:10:40.640 --> 00:10:43.200
And it turns out what they collapsed into is a black hole.

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:49.380
And this was the very first evidence that black holes could exist in reality, in the universe.

00:10:49.380 --> 00:10:53.280
