But if you were to slice like this, you have less signal up here and more signal down here.

00:44:21.660 --> 00:44:25.000
Already the plot told us so much about what we're looking at.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:25.300
Yeah.

00:44:25.540 --> 00:44:29.660
So before we hit a picture, you're like, oh, we think we're onto something here, right?

00:44:29.660 --> 00:44:30.160
Yes.

00:44:30.160 --> 00:44:31.560
It was super exciting.

00:44:31.560 --> 00:44:36.740
But then we were very careful because we thought, okay, there's a lot we can talk from this plot,

00:44:36.740 --> 00:44:39.360
but let's not try to get ahead of ourselves.

00:44:39.360 --> 00:44:45.760
Because there are a lot of types of images that could be tweaked to mimic this kind of structure.

00:44:45.920 --> 00:44:52.400
And so that was kind of part of the next stages in which we wanted to split our teams into our big

00:44:52.400 --> 00:44:54.540
imaging team into four independent teams.

00:44:54.540 --> 00:45:00.560
And each team works independently for about seven weeks on analyzing the data in any means they wanted,

00:45:00.560 --> 00:45:03.200
with any software they wanted, any decision they wanted.

00:45:03.200 --> 00:45:07.180
And we came together after seven weeks at a workshop to compare the images.

00:45:07.180 --> 00:45:09.680
And each team submitted a single image.

00:45:09.680 --> 00:45:14.580
And it turns out that the images between the four teams were very, very similar to each other.

00:45:14.580 --> 00:45:16.200
And so that was really exciting.

00:45:16.200 --> 00:45:20.900
And everybody got a ring of the same size, 42 micrach seconds and brighter on the bottom.

00:45:20.900 --> 00:45:25.940
Even though there were kind of some small differences across the images that came from the user-based

00:45:25.940 --> 00:45:30.400
choices in the software, the main structure was there for everyone.

00:45:30.400 --> 00:45:35.560
And I think that was one of my favorite days in the collaboration because we had so much fun that day.

00:45:35.560 --> 00:45:39.600
It was such a big relief because we were using so many different techniques,

00:45:39.600 --> 00:45:44.000
kind of imaging software that we weren't sure we would all get the same answer.

00:45:44.120 --> 00:45:46.160
So we were really relieved that we did.

