That was a must.

00:46:07.340 --> 00:46:07.540
Perfect.

00:46:07.540 --> 00:46:08.360
Yeah.

00:46:08.360 --> 00:46:10.420
But we changed the lyrics to Blackpool Shadow.

00:46:10.420 --> 00:46:16.240
If you're taking petabytes of data and running them through a bunch of algorithms until they come down to megabytes,

00:46:16.240 --> 00:46:19.580
or you said the final picture is actually like less than one meg.

00:46:19.580 --> 00:46:19.780
Yeah.

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:23.240
Then, you know, what you're seeing, is that actually what you're seeing?

00:46:23.240 --> 00:46:26.100
Or is that artifacts built up along the way, right?

00:46:26.100 --> 00:46:30.280
So this must have been really comforting to try these different algorithms and go, they all come up with the same picture.

00:46:30.280 --> 00:46:30.620
Yeah.

00:46:30.700 --> 00:46:37.160
I think we were confident about what the data were telling us, but we wanted to make sure that we understood how our software were responding to the data.

00:46:37.160 --> 00:46:44.360
So, you know, from kind of objective perspective, when we looked at the data plots, we knew what it was telling us.

00:46:44.360 --> 00:46:50.800
But we wanted to make sure that we looked through every avenue of possible ways of creating images that look similar to the data.

00:46:50.800 --> 00:46:57.040
And in fact, it's really very hard to create images that don't look like what we have.

00:46:57.400 --> 00:47:04.840
And so no matter how much we tweaked our software, we would always end up with something very similar to the final image.

00:47:04.840 --> 00:47:10.520
But we still wanted to put our software through this test and do a kind of process in which we would test it.

00:47:10.520 --> 00:47:19.940
And in the end, the final stage ended up being trying to find what is the best kind of combinations of our software choices that gave us the best image.

00:47:19.940 --> 00:47:26.500
Because we generated so many images with user-based choices, and they ended up pretty similar to each other with the base structure.

00:47:26.580 --> 00:47:27.820
But how do you pick one image?

00:47:27.820 --> 00:47:31.180
So that was kind of the dilemma we had at the final.

00:47:31.180 --> 00:47:33.160
We didn't know how to pick a single image.

00:47:33.160 --> 00:47:40.600
So we decided to create these kind of fake data sets that mimicked our data in which we knew the real truth images.

00:47:40.600 --> 00:47:43.240
And they looked like rings or disks or double sources.

00:47:43.240 --> 00:47:53.900
And then we made our softwares go through thousands of combinations of these parameters and kind of tested how well they could reproduce all four of them, all four images.

00:47:54.180 --> 00:47:57.160
And then the ones that were kind of, we ranked them.

00:47:57.160 --> 00:48:00.180
And then number one was the best image for each software.

00:48:00.180 --> 00:48:08.260
And then the final image, you know, the famous image of a black hole is actually just the average of the three software images, the three best images from the software.

00:48:08.700 --> 00:48:11.680
And this is also only one image of the black hole.

00:48:11.680 --> 00:48:13.200
This is only April 11.

00:48:13.200 --> 00:48:17.040
We observed M87 for four days in 2017.

00:48:17.040 --> 00:48:20.660
So we have four images of this black hole from 2017.

00:48:20.660 --> 00:48:22.200
And they all look the same.

00:48:22.200 --> 00:48:28.360
And they all went through separate day observing, kind of separate processing, and always giving the same answer.

00:48:28.600 --> 00:48:30.780
So you all are pretty sure that this is the picture.

00:48:30.780 --> 00:48:31.440
Absolutely.

00:48:31.440 --> 00:48:33.580
At least this is the radio astronomy picture.

00:48:33.580 --> 00:48:36.660
Yeah, this is the picture at 230 gigahertz.

00:48:36.660 --> 00:48:37.660
Yeah, exactly.

00:48:37.660 --> 00:48:44.260
There's also pictures of that general space with Hubble and some other things that you laid out.

00:48:44.520 --> 00:48:52.080
Yes, this is a really fun part of our campaign also, because obviously we're trying, the purpose of our experiment is to learn about black holes.

00:48:52.080 --> 00:48:55.100
We want, I mean, these objects are super fascinating.

00:48:55.100 --> 00:49:00.040
They're kind of mind boggling in how they exist and what they do to galactic environments.

00:49:00.360 --> 00:49:03.520
These jets are enormous and they're pierced through entire galaxies.

00:49:03.520 --> 00:49:07.260
And yet they come from a very tiny part of the galaxy itself.

00:49:07.260 --> 00:49:12.640
And so in really understanding black holes, it's obviously really useful to look at one up close.

00:49:12.640 --> 00:49:17.880
But we need to combine that knowledge with how it looks across all colors, all wavelengths.

00:49:17.880 --> 00:49:25.960
And so we had a big multi-wavelength campaign at the same time as these observations across lots of different instruments.

00:49:25.960 --> 00:49:32.820
So we had instruments in the high energy, in the X-ray, infrared, in optical, and also other radio wavelengths.

00:49:32.820 --> 00:49:37.440
So we had a lot of partnerships with other observatories too, to make that happen.

00:49:37.440 --> 00:49:41.400
And we learned a great deal about the black hole and its jet through that process.

00:49:41.400 --> 00:49:41.720
Yeah.

00:49:41.720 --> 00:49:47.080
It seems that black holes, supermassive black holes are a fundamental part of galaxies almost, right?

00:49:47.080 --> 00:49:47.640
Absolutely.

00:49:47.640 --> 00:49:50.200
They live in the centers of most galaxies.

00:49:50.200 --> 00:49:54.800
M87 is one of the special ones because it has this big jet coming out of it.

00:49:55.120 --> 00:49:58.840
So it's very nice to get a look at one that has a jet up close.

00:49:58.840 --> 00:50:04.980
And actually, our Milky Way black hole, Sagittarius A star, is one of the very common, boring ones.

00:50:04.980 --> 00:50:13.780
And so the fact that we can have both of them and look at both of them is kind of special because it gives us kind of two very different classes of black holes.

00:50:13.780 --> 00:50:15.960
That end up looking very much the same.

00:50:15.960 --> 00:50:18.440
Sagittarius A star's image looks a lot like M87.

00:50:18.760 --> 00:50:24.740
This is really just because even though they're totally different black holes, they differ in mass by a factor of about 1500.

00:50:24.740 --> 00:50:27.700
And our Milky Way is a spiral galaxy, right?

00:50:27.700 --> 00:50:32.660
But M87's galaxy is elliptical and it's much older and much bigger than our Milky Way.

00:50:32.660 --> 00:50:36.460
And M87 has a jet and Sagittarius A star doesn't seem to have one.

00:50:36.460 --> 00:50:38.440
So there are two very different black holes.

00:50:38.560 --> 00:50:44.980
And yet, once you get up close, it's really just the effects of gravity is so strong that it's really all you see.

00:50:44.980 --> 00:50:47.060
And it's so cool that they look the same.

00:50:47.060 --> 00:50:47.900
Yeah, it is amazing.

00:50:47.900 --> 00:50:53.060
I guess it's worth just pointing out just how large the M87 black hole is.

00:50:53.240 --> 00:50:54.040
Oh, yes.

00:50:54.040 --> 00:50:59.340
The shadow of the M87 black hole could fit our entire solar system very easily.

00:50:59.340 --> 00:51:05.580
It could, you know, the orbit of Pluto would be about in the middle, in the kind of mid-range inside the shadow.

00:51:05.580 --> 00:51:11.780
And Voyager 1, which is the furthest human-made object, would be just at the edge of the shadow right now.

00:51:11.780 --> 00:51:12.760
Yeah, that's incredible.

00:51:12.760 --> 00:51:13.380
Very, very big.

00:51:13.380 --> 00:51:15.580
If it were there, it would get sucked back in.

00:51:15.580 --> 00:51:18.220
But if it were unaffected, it would be at the edge.

00:51:19.080 --> 00:51:22.840
Yeah, so also 6.5 billion solar masses.

00:51:22.840 --> 00:51:23.960
That's right.

00:51:23.960 --> 00:51:24.520
Yeah.

00:51:24.520 --> 00:51:25.320
That's really large.

00:51:25.320 --> 00:51:26.620
That's a lot of mass.

00:51:26.620 --> 00:51:29.540
It's actually one of the heaviest black holes in our universe.

00:51:29.540 --> 00:51:37.100
I think the current heaviest is about 10, I think 10 billion solar masses, maybe a little more.

00:51:37.100 --> 00:51:38.940
Wow, so that's not that much larger, yeah.

00:51:38.940 --> 00:51:41.360
Yeah, it was one of the pretty larger ones.

