00:51:55.560 --> 00:51:56.220
What now?

00:51:56.220 --> 00:51:59.100
Since our 2017 campaign, we've kept observing.

00:51:59.100 --> 00:52:08.220
We observed in 2018, where we added one telescope and increased our bandwidths, where we can have more sensitivity and cooler observations of magnetic fields.

00:52:08.220 --> 00:52:14.940
We also observed in 2021, which was a kind of mid-COVID observation, which was a very strange one.

00:52:14.940 --> 00:52:18.560
And in 2022, we added two new stations after that.

00:52:18.560 --> 00:52:21.060
So we're now up to 11 with the EHT.

00:52:21.060 --> 00:52:24.360
And we're trying to expand our array to have more telescopes.

00:52:24.360 --> 00:52:29.360
So there's currently an effort called the Next Generation Event Horizon Telescope.

00:52:29.360 --> 00:52:43.580
So the EHT so far only borrowed telescopes that just happened to be at the right locations that were actually built for completely different science programs, just radio telescopes that were able to observe at the frequency we wanted and at the right place.

00:52:43.580 --> 00:52:47.560
So we didn't have much of a control over the locations of the telescopes.

00:52:47.560 --> 00:52:53.300
And so in order to see more of our image, for example, to see the jet in MA-7, we need a lot more telescopes.

00:52:53.300 --> 00:52:57.880
So the Next Generation EHT plans to have more control over where telescopes are going to be put.

00:52:57.880 --> 00:53:03.040
So we're planning to get smaller dishes because we have the sensitivity now with the current EHT.

00:53:03.040 --> 00:53:11.180
Smaller dishes at the locations where we need them, where we have holes in our virtual mirror to recover the structure.

00:53:11.180 --> 00:53:13.480
And eventually, we'd like to observe more often.

00:53:13.480 --> 00:53:15.500
So now we only observe two weeks a year.

00:53:15.500 --> 00:53:19.300
We want to be able to observe every two weeks or every month.

00:53:19.300 --> 00:53:21.520
And eventually, we could make movies of M-87.

00:53:21.520 --> 00:53:26.380
And also, if we have enough telescopes, we would be able to make movies of Sagittarius A-Star as well.

00:53:26.400 --> 00:53:32.780
And that will really show us the connection between the black holes, the gas swirling around it, and its jet and magnetic fields.

00:53:32.780 --> 00:53:35.320
I think we could learn so much about black holes through that.

00:53:35.320 --> 00:53:36.660
It would be so exciting.

00:53:36.660 --> 00:53:40.500
You could get precise speed of the accretion disk and how it evolves.

00:53:40.500 --> 00:53:41.020
Yeah.

00:53:41.020 --> 00:53:43.800
And that's about a 10-year time scale.

00:53:44.060 --> 00:53:51.620
In the far future, in kind of 20 to 30 years, members of our team are currently actively thinking about putting satellites into space.

00:53:51.620 --> 00:53:57.980
Since we're running out of Earth's diameter to make a bigger telescope, there's only two ways to make your telescope bigger.

00:53:57.980 --> 00:54:03.220
Either make the separation bigger or go to higher frequency so we have higher resolution.

00:54:03.440 --> 00:54:07.980
And because of the Earth's atmosphere and the size of the Earth, we're limited in both.

00:54:07.980 --> 00:54:14.060
But by going into space, we'd go above the atmosphere so you can go to higher frequency and you could have larger distances.

00:54:14.600 --> 00:54:23.260
So by putting satellites into space, we could have enough resolution to maybe see up to 10 or even 50 more shadows of black holes, which would be really cool.

00:54:23.260 --> 00:54:31.560
And then we'd have amazing sharp images of the two that we know and love to really test theories of gravity, which would be terribly exciting.

00:54:31.680 --> 00:54:35.280
But of course, the technology to do that is not there yet, but it is moving forward.

00:54:35.280 --> 00:54:38.060
And it's something we're thinking actively about.

00:54:38.060 --> 00:54:38.480
Getting there.

